  </div>
</header>

<!-- STATS STRIP -->
<div class="stats-band">
  <div class="wrap stats-grid">
    <div class="st reveal"><div class="n">3 lifecycles</div><div class="l">customer, consultant, and creator</div></div>
    <div class="st reveal"><div class="n">15% of 2.5M</div><div class="l">dormant customers reactivated</div></div>
    <div class="st reveal"><div class="n">Lytics + Talon.One</div><div class="l">platforms I onboarded and manage</div></div>
    <div class="st reveal"><div class="n">All of mktg</div><div class="l">audience for the AI adoption I lead</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- APPROACH -->
<section id="approach">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head reveal">
      <div class="rule"><span class="rule-d"></span></div>
      <div class="eyebrow">How I work</div>
      <h2 class="section">The through-line</h2>
      <p class="lead">Whether it's a lifecycle, a loyalty motion, or a new platform, it comes back to the same three things.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="why-grid">
      <div class="why-card reveal">
        <div class="k">Hands-on builder</div>
        <p>The lifecycles, the tools, the reporting. I build the working thing and stay on it after launch.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="why-card reveal">
        <div class="k">I connect the teams</div>
        <p>When we reorganized, our CMO called this a "Swiss army knife" position. I sit across digital, product, analytics, copy, dev, and IT, and keep work moving between them.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="why-card reveal">
        <div class="k">I own the data</div>
        <p>I lead and own our Adobe Analytics platform: the analysis and reporting I build for the team, plus administering it so the rest of the org can use it too.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CAPABILITIES -->
<section id="capabilities" class="band">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head reveal">
      <div class="eyebrow">What I do</div>
      <h2 class="section">What I do, and the work behind it</h2>
      <p class="lead">Filter by area. Each one is real work, not a job description.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="filters reveal" id="filters">
      <button class="chip active" data-f="all">All</button>
      <button class="chip" data-f="build">Building &amp; Shipping</button>
      <button class="chip" data-f="lifecycle">Lifecycle &amp; CRM</button>
      <button class="chip" data-f="vendor">Martech &amp; Integrations</button>
      <button class="chip" data-f="partner">Activations &amp; Tracking</button>
      <button class="chip" data-f="data">Analytics</button>
      <button class="chip" data-f="collab">Cross-functional</button>
    </div>
    <div class="map-grid" id="mapGrid"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SELECTED WORK -->
<section id="work">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head reveal">
      <div class="eyebrow">Selected work</div>
      <h2 class="section">A few things I've built, start to finish</h2>
      <p class="lead">Open any card for the full arc: the situation, what I did, and where it landed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cases" id="cases"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- TOOLBOX -->
<section id="toolbox" class="band">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head reveal">
      <div class="eyebrow">Toolbox &amp; range</div>
      <h2 class="section">The stack I work in every day</h2>
      <p class="lead">Lifecycle and loyalty run on a CDP, an ESP, a loyalty engine, a CMS, and analytics. I work across all of them, and I bring on new ones when we need them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tools reveal">
      <div class="tool"><b>Lytics</b> (our CDP)</div>
      <div class="tool"><b>Customer.io</b> (ESP, lifecycle sends)</div>
      <div class="tool"><b>Talon.One</b> (loyalty &amp; promotions)</div>
      <div class="tool"><b>Contentstack</b> (CMS)</div>
      <div class="tool"><b>Adobe Analytics</b></div>
      <div class="tool"><b>Algolia</b> (search &amp; recommendations)</div>
      <div class="tool"><b>Airtable</b> (program ops)</div>
      <div class="tool"><b>AI tools</b> (built in-house)</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CLOSE -->
<div class="wrap close">
  <div class="rule" style="max-width:220px;margin:0 auto 4px;"><span class="rule-d"></span></div>
  <h2>My job is the health of the customer portfolio.</h2>
  <p>Lifecycle campaigns, the loyalty program, or the tools behind them, I keep the work pointed at the customer. Someone has to be.</p>
</div>

<footer class="wrap">Payton Stastny · Program Manager, Marketing · Selected Work</footer>

<script>
/* ---------- What I do ---------- */
const MAP = [
  {c:"build", seg:"The tools behind the work",
   proof:"A mix of what I built in-house, like an AI-assisted email segment builder and reporting dashboards, and the third-party platforms I onboarded and manage for the team."},
  {c:"build", seg:"Ran it like a product",
   proof:"I scoped, prioritized, and shipped these in pieces, then kept improving them on real feedback so the team actually adopted them."},
  {c:"lifecycle", seg:"Built our lifecycle journeys",
   proof:"Built the full customer journey in <b>Customer.io</b>, from first purchase through repeat, lapse, and win-back, plus consultant and creator journeys designed to connect to it."},
  {c:"lifecycle", seg:"Personalization inside the segments",
   proof:"Beyond static segments, I set up dynamic personalization so one send adapts to the person. A reactivation email surfaces the category someone bought from most, so a laundry buyer and a warmer buyer see different offers in the same campaign."},
  {c:"lifecycle", seg:"Ran the win-back campaign",
   proof:"Reactivated <b>15% of 2.5M</b> dormant customers with offers personalized to what each was most likely to come back for, inside clear dormancy rules and finance-approved margin guardrails."},
  {c:"lifecycle", seg:"Brought SMS and app push into the mix",
   proof:"It was on me to onboard SMS into our lifecycle and to use the app for push, so we can retain and re-activate customers beyond the inbox."},
  {c:"vendor", seg:"Developed and manage our CDP",
   proof:"I led the build-out of our CDP and manage it day to day, setting it up so marketers can use it to activate, retain, and reactivate customers, not just store data."},
  {c:"vendor", seg:"Brought on new platforms",
   proof:"I evaluate, make the case for, and onboard the tools we need, like our CDP and our loyalty engine, then set up how the team actually uses them."},
  {c:"partner", seg:"Built engagement features in our app",
   proof:"Set up tasks and challenges inside our app, the kind of in-app activity that gives people a reason to come back, with tracking wired in so we can see what's working."},
  {c:"data", seg:"Lead and own our analytics",
   proof:"I own our Adobe Analytics platform: both the analysis and reporting I build for the team, and administering the platform so the rest of the org can use it."},
  {c:"data", seg:"Turn the numbers into decisions",
   proof:"I built the lifecycle dashboards we use to see what's actually working, with a bias toward incremental lift over vanity metrics, and reprioritize where the team spends effort."},
  {c:"collab", seg:"Lead AI adoption for marketing",
   proof:"I rolled AI out across the department: the training, the tooling, and the workflows that made it stick."},
  {c:"collab", seg:"Line up cross-team launches",
   proof:"When a launch touches email, the CDP, the loyalty engine, and dev at once, I sequence the pieces, keep everyone aligned, and flag blockers before they hit the deadline."}
];
const LABELS={build:"Building & Shipping",lifecycle:"Lifecycle & CRM",vendor:"Martech & Integrations",partner:"Activations & Tracking",data:"Analytics",collab:"Cross-functional"};
const grid=document.getElementById('mapGrid');
MAP.forEach(m=>{
  const el=document.createElement('div');
  el.className='map-card reveal'; el.dataset.c=m.c;
  el.innerHTML=`<span class="tag">${LABELS[m.c]}</span><div class="seg">${m.seg}</div><div class="proof">${m.proof}</div>`;
  grid.appendChild(el);
});
document.getElementById('filters').addEventListener('click',e=>{
  if(!e.target.classList.contains('chip'))return;
  document.querySelectorAll('.chip').forEach(c=>c.classList.remove('active'));
  e.target.classList.add('active');
  const f=e.target.dataset.f;
  document.querySelectorAll('.map-card').forEach(card=>card.classList.toggle('hide', f!=='all' && card.dataset.c!==f));
});

/* ---------- Selected work (start to finish) ---------- */
const CASES=[
  {t:"Built our lifecycle program from the ground up",sub:"Customer, consultant & creator journeys",
   sit:"We had <b>no structured lifecycle</b>, and three different audiences that each needed one: customers, the consultants who sell, and creators. None of it existed.",
   steps:[
     "<b>Built the customer journey first.</b> The full path in Customer.io, from first purchase through repeat, lapse, and win-back.",
     "<b>Added consultant and creator journeys.</b> Each audience got its own onboarding, engagement, and retention, built to connect and hand off as people move between roles.",
     "<b>Brought in more than email.</b> Onboarded SMS into the lifecycle and set up app push, so we reach people wherever they are, not just the inbox.",
     "<b>Ran a win-back inside it.</b> Reactivated 15% of 2.5M dormant customers with offers personalized to what each was most likely to come back for, inside clear dormancy rules and finance-approved margin guardrails, and read it on incremental returns rather than raw redemptions.",
     "<b>Built the reporting to run it.</b> As the analytics owner, I built the dashboard that shows how each lifecycle is performing, sign-ups, engagement, retention, and redemption, so we manage on numbers instead of guesses."
   ],
   result:"Three connected lifecycles that didn't exist before, across email, SMS, and app push, the win-back program living inside them, and the reporting to keep improving all three."},
  {t:"Developed and now run our CDP for the marketing teams",sub:"Lytics · integration · segmentation",
   sit:"Customer data was scattered across systems with <b>no unified profiles</b>, so the teams couldn't segment or personalize with any confidence.",
   steps:[
     "<b>Made the case and picked the tool.</b> Weighed the options against what we actually needed and landed on Lytics.",
     "<b>Led the build-out.</b> Owned the implementation and the Lytics to Customer.io integration, including working through the sync issues along the way.",
     "<b>Set it up for the teams.</b> Built the audiences and segments the marketing teams pull from, so they can use the CDP to activate, retain, and reactivate customers.",
     "<b>Manage it day to day.</b> I maintain it, add new segments as needs change, and keep it reliable as the team leans on it more."
   ],
   result:"A CDP the marketing teams use every day to reach customers, and the data layer our lifecycle and loyalty work runs on. I've reused the same approach to bring on other tools since."},
  {t:"Built an AI-assisted email segment builder",sub:"Internal tool · self-serve · speed",
   sit:"Building audiences for email was <b>slow and technical</b>, so the non-technical marketers had to wait on someone else every time they wanted to send.",
   steps:[
     "<b>Sat with the email team.</b> Watched how they were building and requesting segments, and figured out what kept slowing them down.",
     "<b>Built the tool.</b> An AI-assisted builder that lets someone define a segment in plain language.",
     "<b>Made it real, not a demo.</b> Connected it to our actual segmentation logic so the output was usable.",
     "<b>Tuned it with the team.</b> Refined it on their feedback until it fit how they actually work."
